Week 3 Lab Companion: Regression for Association

Companion document with more advanced coding methods

Author

Chris Zuidema for ENVH 556 Autumn 2024

This document was rendered on October 17, 2024.

NOTE: This document was developed in 2021 and has not been updated. You are free to use this document as an additional resource.

Purpose

This document is a companion to the Week3Lab.Rmd. The purpose is to provide additional and somewhat more sophisticated coding methods to supplement the approaches demonstrated in Lab 3; you may find these more advanced coding methods useful for your own work. Our coding goals for Week3Lab.Rmd were clarity and transparency to support learning about regression. Here we demonstrate some techniques that will scale well (for example to many regression models), reduce code repetition, and reduce the amount of âhard codingâ in the analysis, but that are less explicit and may obscure what is going on âbehind the scenesâ a bit. As with Week3Lab.Rmd, this document will use the snapshot data.

Regression analysis

Week3Lab.Rmd takes a more manual approach to regression modeling by specifying each of the seasonal models separately and assigning each model fit to its own object. This approach is clear and easy to follow, but you can see how this would quickly become a burdensome exercise potentially fraught with errors due to its reliance on copy/paste and repeated code. Imagine if we had 20 seasons instead of 3. In this section, we explore the general nesting workflow, where data is grouped and modeling steps occur âwithinâ a dataframe. Aside from managing analysis steps with groups programmatically, these functions package regression output in dataframes that are ggplot friendly, thus minimizing the data wrangling required before plotting.

You can find more information about the nested workflow here:

  • Tidyverse âNested Dataâ
  • Bookdown âMany Modelsâ
#-----regression for association-----

# Common model (Table 4), season-specific LUR from Mercer et al, 2011

# specify the "common model"
frml <-
  as.formula(ln_nox ~ D2A1 + A1_50 + A23_400 + Pop_5000 + D2C + Int_3000 + D2Comm)

# create tibble with nested seasonal models
season_mods_nested <- snapshot %>%
  
  # group by season, then "nest"
  group_by(seasonfac) %>% 
  nest() %>% 
  
  # fit regression model for each season and generate summary, glance, augment,
  # and in-sample prediction outputs with prediction intervals.
  mutate(model = map(data, ~lm(frml, data = .x)),
         summary = map(model, summary), 
         glanced = map(model, glance),
         augmented = map(model, augment),
         preds = map2(model, data, 
                      ~as.data.frame(predict(.x, .y, interval = "prediction")) )
         
         )

# show tibble
season_mods_nested
# A tibble: 3 Ã 7
# Groups:   seasonfac [3]
  seasonfac data                model  summary    glanced  augmented preds 
  <fct>     <list>              <list> <list>     <list>   <list>    <list>
1 Summer    <tibble [148 Ã 78]> <lm>   <smmry.lm> <tibble> <tibble>  <df>  
2 Fall      <tibble [152 Ã 78]> <lm>   <smmry.lm> <tibble> <tibble>  <df>  
3 Winter    <tibble [149 Ã 78]> <lm>   <smmry.lm> <tibble> <tibble>  <df>

You can see season_mods is a grouped tibble with list-columns for each of the non-grouping variables. (Recall that âseasonfacâ is the grouping variable.) Next weâll demonstrate how to access these outputs separately to show what outputs the glance() (model summaries) and augment() (information about each observation like predictions and residuals) functions produce. Note that as an alternative you can incorporate the unnest() step into the pipeline in the previous chunk. We showed the summary(), glance(), augment(), and predict() functions above, but you can include or remove functions to suit your needs.

#-----unnest-----

# unnest glanced object - `glance()` provides model summaries
unnest(season_mods_nested, glanced)

Regression predictions

Output from nest() workflow

In the previous chunks we calculated in-sample predictions with augment(). The nesting workflow makes plotting those predictions easy:

#-----plot obs pred in sample-----

# calculate range of data
r <- range(season_mods[, c("ln_nox", ".fitted")])

# plot observations vs predictions for each season
ggplot(season_mods, aes(x = .fitted, y = ln_nox)) + 
  geom_point(shape = "o") + 
  facet_wrap(~seasonfac, nrow = 1) + 
  lims(x = r, y = r) +
  coord_fixed() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  labs(title = "In-sample Predictions", 
       x = "In-sample predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))",
       y = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))"
       ) + 
  theme_bw()

Calculating predictions programmatically

In Week3Lab.Rmd we specified each of the out-of-sample predictions we were interested in separately, for example:


fall_preds_from_summer <- 
  predict(lm_summer, snapshot[snapshot$season == 2,], interval = "prediction")

This is quite clear whatâs happening, but again, it requires us to specify the model, the data subset, and the object name for each set of out-of-sample predictions of interest.

Next weâll demonstrate how to calculate the season-specific predictions in the dataset for all seasons programmatically. While augment() conveniently gave us âin-sampleâ predictions, the following approach will give us both âin-sampleâ predictions (e.g.Â using the summer model to make predictions in summer) and âout-of-sampleâ predictions (e.g.Â using the summer model to make predictions in winter). The extra step involved with this approach comes after this chunk. It is selecting the output of interest, for example, the âWinter_â columns from the Summer âseasonfacâ rows.

#-----predictions with dplyr-----

# first, extract models from earlier regression procedures for convenience, 
# setting the names of the models to match with their season
models <- season_mods_nested$model %>%
  setNames(as.character(season_mods_nested$seasonfac))

# use lapply and an anonymous function to loop through the models
allseas_both <- lapply(names(models), function(i){
  
  # add the predictions, intervals, and residuals for each season
  predict(models[[i]], snapshot, interval = "prediction") %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    mutate(resid = snapshot[["ln_nox"]]-fit) %>%
    
    # rename columns to correspond to the season model
    rename_all(function(x){paste0(i, "_", x)})
  
  }) %>% 
  
  # bind list of dataframes together
  reduce(cbind) %>% 
  
  # add to snapshot dataframe
  bind_cols(snapshot, .)

# inspect predictions and residuals
allseas_both %>% 
  select(seasonfac, ln_nox, matches("_fit|_lwr|_upr|_resid")) %>% 
  mutate_if(is.double, round, 3)

Plot predictions

We can define a flexible plot function to prevent repeating our plotting code: (Note that we will describe how to write functions in the Week 4 lab.)

#-----define plot function-----

# make plot function
plot_func <- function(df = allseas_both, x_var, y_var, seas, 
                      x_lab, y_lab, plot_title){

  # create function variable names with `enquo`
  x <- enquo(x_var)
  y <- enquo(y_var)
  
  # get range of data to define the plotting range in the axes
  r <- df %>% 
    filter(seasonfac == seas) %>% 
    select(Summer_fit, Fall_fit, Winter_fit, ln_nox) %>% 
    range()
  
  # make plots
  df %>%
    filter(seasonfac == seas) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = !!x, y = !!y)) +
    geom_point(shape = "o", alpha = 0.8) +
    lims(x = r, y = r) +
    coord_fixed() +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
    labs(title = plot_title, 
         x = x_lab,
         y = y_lab
         ) + 
    theme_bw()

}

With the allseas_both dataframe (specified by default) we can plot in- and out-of-sample predictions like we did in Week3Lab.Rmd with our function:

#-----summer in and out of sample-----

# plot the predictions vs. data for summer, both in-sample and out of sample

# in-sample plot
p_in <- plot_func(x_var = Summer_fit, y_var = ln_nox, seas = "Summer", 
                  x_lab = "In-sample predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                  y_lab = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                  plot_title = "In-sample")
 
# out-of-sample plot (predictions from the winter model)
p_out <- plot_func(x_var = Winter_fit, y_var = ln_nox, seas = "Summer", 
                   x_lab = "Out-of-sample predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                   y_lab = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                   plot_title = "Out-of-sample (from winter model)" )

# combine plots
ggarrange(p_in, p_out, ncol = 2, 
          top = "Summer Model ln(NOx) Predictions", 
          bottom = "Best fit line is red; 1:1 line is blue")

Here is an alternate approach for plotting all predictions from a single season simultaneously using facet wrap():

#-----plot all predictions-----

# create temporary dataframe for ggplot
temp <- allseas_both %>% 
  select(seasonfac, ln_nox, contains("_fit")) %>% 
  filter(seasonfac == "Summer") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = contains("_fit"), names_to = "season_fit", 
               values_to = "fit") %>% 
  mutate(season_fit = factor(str_remove(season_fit, "_fit"), 
                             levels = c("Summer", "Fall", "Winter")) )

# get range for plots
  r <- temp %>% 
    select(fit, ln_nox) %>% 
    range()
  
# make plot
pred_plot <- ggplot(data = temp, aes(x = fit, y = ln_nox) ) +
    geom_point(shape = "o", alpha = 0.8) + 
    facet_wrap(~season_fit, nrow = 1) +
    lims(x = r, y = r) +
    coord_fixed() +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
    labs(title = "Predictions with Summer Model", 
         x = "Predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))",
         y = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))"
         ) + 
    theme_bw()

# show plot
pred_plot

#-----define plot function-----

# make plot function
plot_func <- function(df = allseas_both, x_var, y_var, seas, 
                      x_lab, y_lab, plot_title){

  # create function variable names with `enquo`
  x <- enquo(x_var)
  y <- enquo(y_var)
  
  # get range of data to define the plotting range in the axes
  r <- df %>% 
    filter(seasonfac == seas) %>% 
    select(Summer_fit, Fall_fit, Winter_fit, ln_nox) %>% 
    range()
  
  # make plots
  df %>%
    filter(seasonfac == seas) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = !!x, y = !!y)) +
    geom_point(shape = "o", alpha = 0.8) +
    lims(x = r, y = r) +
    coord_fixed() +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
    labs(title = plot_title, 
         x = x_lab,
         y = y_lab
         ) + 
    theme_bw()

}

#-----summer in and out of sample-----

# plot the predictions vs. data for summer, both in-sample and out of sample

# in-sample plot
p_in <- plot_func(x_var = Summer_fit, y_var = ln_nox, seas = "Summer", 
                  x_lab = "In-sample predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                  y_lab = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                  plot_title = "In-sample")
 
# out-of-sample plot (predictions from the winter model)
p_out <- plot_func(x_var = Winter_fit, y_var = ln_nox, seas = "Summer", 
                   x_lab = "Out-of-sample predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                   y_lab = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))", 
                   plot_title = "Out-of-sample (from winter model)" )

# combine plots
ggarrange(p_in, p_out, ncol = 2, 
          top = "Summer Model ln(NOx) Predictions", 
          bottom = "Best fit line is red; 1:1 line is blue")

#-----plot all predictions-----

# create temporary dataframe for ggplot
temp <- allseas_both %>% 
  select(seasonfac, ln_nox, contains("_fit")) %>% 
  filter(seasonfac == "Summer") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = contains("_fit"), names_to = "season_fit", 
               values_to = "fit") %>% 
  mutate(season_fit = factor(str_remove(season_fit, "_fit"), 
                             levels = c("Summer", "Fall", "Winter")) )

# get range for plots
  r <- temp %>% 
    select(fit, ln_nox) %>% 
    range()
  
# make plot
pred_plot <- ggplot(data = temp, aes(x = fit, y = ln_nox) ) +
    geom_point(shape = "o", alpha = 0.8) + 
    facet_wrap(~season_fit, nrow = 1) +
    lims(x = r, y = r) +
    coord_fixed() +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "blue") +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
    labs(title = "Predictions with Summer Model", 
         x = "Predicted ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))",
         y = "Observed ln(NOx) (ln(ppb))"
         ) + 
    theme_bw()

# show plot
